  "prompt": "How does a hydraulic brake work? Describe in brief",
  "response": "Here's a brief explanation of how a hydraulic brake works:\n\n1. Basic Principle:\n- Uses fluid pressure to transmit force from the brake pedal to the brake pads\n- Converts mechanical force into hydraulic pressure\n\n2. Key Components:\n- Master cylinder\n- Brake fluid\n- Brake lines\n- Brake calipers\n- Brake pads\n- Brake rotors/discs\n\n3. Brake Operation Process:\n- When driver presses brake pedal, it pushes a piston inside the master cylinder\n- Piston applies pressure to brake fluid in the cylinder\n- Pressurized fluid travels through brake lines to wheel cylinders/calipers\n- Fluid pressure forces brake pads to press against the rotors\n- Friction between pads and rotors slows or stops the wheel\n\n4. Key Benefits:\n- Provides consistent and powerful braking\n- Multiplies force applied by the driver\n- Distributes braking force evenly to all wheels\n- Offers precise and predictable braking performance\n\n5. Force Multiplication:\n- Hydraulic system allows small input force to create large braking force\n- Follows Pascal's principle of fluid pressure transmission\n\nThis system efficiently converts driver input into vehicle deceleration through fluid pressure mechanics.",
